REVIEWS

voltages without Ca2ϩ than in Slo1 alone (107, 162). In addition, in the presence of ␤1, ␤2⌬N, or ␤4, the activated state of the VSD is stabilized by various degrees (7, 26, 107, 129, 162). More focused studies, examining subsets of the transitions within the HA model, suggest that the presence of ␤1 alters the two Ca2ϩ sensors of the channel differentially (147). As noted earlier, the RCK1 Ca2ϩ sensor has a lower afﬁnity than the RCK2 Ca2ϩ bowl sensor, but its coupling to the ion conduction gate is approximately two times stronger. With ␤1, the Kd value of the RCK1 Ca2ϩ sensor when the gate is open (Ko) decreases by fourfold (i.e., afﬁnity is higher) to a level similar to that of the RCK2 Ca2ϩ bowl sensor and increases the coupling strength (C in the HA model) by fourfold. The RCK2 Ca2ϩ bowl sensor is less affected by ␤1; the Kd value when the gate is closed (Kc) increases by approximately two to threefold and the enhancement in coupling strength is approximately twofold. Therefore, the RCK1 Ca2ϩ sensor contributes more prominently to the increase in the overall Ca2ϩ sensitivity seen in Slo1 ϩ ␤1 channels. A qualitatively similar increase in coupling between the Ca2ϩ sensors and the ion conduction gate is reported for Slo1 ϩ ␤4 (162). The characteristic slowing of the activation and deactivation kinetics of ionic currents at low [Ca2ϩ]i when ␤1, ␤2⌬N, or ␤4 is present is not accompanied by appreciable slowing of “on” or “off” gating charge movements, which predominantly reﬂect the kinetics of the VSD (7, 26). Therefore, the slower ionic currents in Slo1 ϩ ␤1, Slo1 ϩ ␤2⌬N, and Slo1 ϩ ␤4 are probably caused by changes in the kinetics of the ion conduction gate.
␥-Subunits
Frequent BK channel openings at negative resting membrane potentials were once interpreted to signify a high level of [Ca2ϩ]i. This conventional thinking was shattered by the recordings from rodent cochlear hair cells (153) and also from prostate and breast cancer cells (39); some BK channels do open without much Ca2ϩ at negative voltages. In the aforementioned cancer cells, this characteristic is conferred by LRRC26, the founding member of the ␥-subunit family (177). At the plasma membrane surface, LRRC26 (␥1) possess a single transmembrane segment with a large extracellular NH2-terminal domain containing ﬁve leucine-rich repeat motifs (FIGURE 1A) (177). Overexpression of LRRC26 (␥1) shifts the half-activation voltage of macroscopic ionic currents without Ca2ϩ from Ͼ160 to ϳ0 mV, similar to that caused by 100 ␮M [Ca2ϩ]i! This remarkable shift in the overall voltage dependence of activation is caused by a 20-fold increase in the strength of coupling between the VSD and the ion conduction gate (D in the HA model). LRRC26 (␥1) is only

one of several LRRC proteins that could function as BK channel auxiliary subunits in a tissue-dependent manner (2, 176); different LRRC proteins appear to inﬂuence the BK channel function to different degrees (176). The stoichiometry between Slo1 and ␥-subunits in native channel complexes is not known. LRRC proteins are capable of interacting with other ion channels; for example, LRRC52 markedly modiﬁes functional properties of Slo3 channels (178), which are activated by alkalization and are critical for fertility (134).
Physicochemical Mechanisms of Regulation by ␤- and ␥-Subunits
Multiple regions of Slo1 and ␤-subunits have been implicated in proper functional coassembly between them: Slo1 transmembrane domain (78, 94, 99, 160), Slo1 cytoplasmic gating ring domain (78, 118), ␤ extracellular linker (46), and ␤ NH2- and COOH-terminal intracellular regions (108, 188). However, the exact physicochemical mechanisms by which the ␤-subunits induce the various functional changes remain unresolved. The probable location of the ␤-subunit [between two adjacent VSDs (FIGURE 4B)] suggests that the ␤-subunit may inﬂuence the VSD energetics (26) through direct interactions and/or indirectly via membrane lipids. How the behavior of the ion conduction gate, most likely located near the selectivity ﬁlter within the central pore domain, is inﬂuenced by the ␤-subunits near the periphery of the channel complex is unclear. The physicochemical mechanism underlying the remarkable effect of LRRC26 (␥1) is also obscure. The functional effects of ␤1 and LRRC26 (␥1) compete, suggesting that LRRC26 (␥1) subunit positions itself between two VSDs near the central pore domain, like ␤-subunits, to alter the coupling between the VSD and the gate (177).
Where Does Ca2؉ Come From?
Many BK channels exist as components of macromolecular signaling complexes so that the channels transduce local signals, whether they be Ca2ϩ or other messengers. One of the best known examples is found in vascular smooth muscle cells. Whereas global increases in [Ca2ϩ]i induce muscle contraction, local and discrete increases in [Ca2ϩ]i mediated by ryanodine receptor channels in the sarcoplasmic reticulum promote vasorelaxation by activating Slo1 ϩ ␤1 channels (18). The local [Ca2ϩ]i near the BK channels in arterial smooth muscle cells has been estimated to be Ն10 ␮M during contraction (115, 196), near or above the estimated Kd values of the Ca2ϩ sensors in Slo1 ϩ ␤1 (147).

184

PHYSIOLOGY • Volume 28 • March 2013 • www.physiologyonline.org

Downloaded from journals.physiology.org/journal/physiologyonline at Univ of Massachusetts (128.119.202.131) on July 21, 2022.

Ca2ϩ inﬂux through plasma membrane ion channels also activates nearby BK channels. Differential effects of the slow Ca2ϩ chelator EGTA and the fast Ca2ϩ chelator BAPTA (197) on neuronal action potential repolarization suggest that the distance between the voltage-gated Ca2ϩ channel pore and the BK channel Ca2ϩ sensor is only ϳ13 nm (100). This distance is surprisingly small because the radius of the transmembrane domain of the BK channel is probably ϳ5 nm and that of the voltage-gated Ca2ϩ channel is expected to be similar, leaving only a few nanometers between the two channels (12). The Ca2ϩ ions entering through voltage-gated Ca2ϩ channels do not travel far to bind to BK channel complexes. An observation in line with this concept was reported earlier in hippocampal neurons: a small unitary inward Ca2ϩ channel opening was suggested to be followed immediately by an outward BK channel opening (88). Consistent with these functional results, multiple types of voltage-gated Ca2ϩ channels (L-type CaV1.2, N-type CaV 2.2, P/Q-type CaV2.1, and potentially T-type CaV3.2) (12, 13, 22, 45) appear capable of forming close physical interactions with BK channel complexes. Additionally, BK channels form complexes with NMDA glutamate receptors (193) and also with IP3 receptor channels (193).
Concluding Remarks
The BK channel is an exemplar model of allosteric regulation of ion channel proteins. The modular components of the BK channel are each capable of activation in response to a speciﬁc energy type: the membrane potential and chemical potential of Ca2ϩ and other ligands. The VSD and gating ring are sensors and transducers that detect and propagate the signals to the “active site” of the protein, namely the ion selectivity ﬁlter and its associated gate. These remarkable features, together with the unusually large unitary conductance, allow the channel to participate in numerous physiological functions. Ⅲ
